07010nam a22012495i 9780691209791DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020018930  a97806912097917 a10.1515/97806912097912doi  a(DE-B1597)554824  a(OCoLC)1202625231  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHV3191b.B374 2021 7aSOC0490002bisacsh04a361.7089/9240732231 aBerman, Lila Corwin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe American Jewish Philanthropic Complex :bThe History of a Multibillion-Dollar Institution /cLila Corwin Berman. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b20 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The State of Philanthropy -- t1. Associations -- t2. Regulations -- t3. Property -- t4. Taxation -- t5. Politics -- t6. Finance and Identity -- t7. The Market -- t8. The Complex -- tConclusion: Reform -- tAcknowledgments -- tArchives and Abbreviations -- tAuthor's Interviews -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first comprehensive history of American Jewish philanthropy and its influence on democracy and capitalismFor years, American Jewish philanthropy has been celebrated as the proudest product of Jewish endeavors in the United States, its virtues extending from the local to the global, the Jewish to the non-Jewish, and modest donations to vast endowments. Yet, as Lila Corwin Berman illuminates in The American Jewish Philanthropic Complex, the history of American Jewish philanthropy reveals the far more complicated reality of changing and uneasy relationships among philanthropy, democracy, and capitalism.With a fresh eye and lucid prose, and relying on previously untapped sources, Berman shows that from its nineteenth-century roots to its apex in the late twentieth century, the American Jewish philanthropic complex tied Jewish institutions to the American state. The government's regulatory efforts-most importantly, tax policies-situated philanthropy at the core of its experiments to maintain the public good without trammeling on the private freedoms of individuals. Jewish philanthropic institutions and leaders gained financial strength, political influence, and state protections within this framework. However, over time, the vast inequalities in resource distribution that marked American state policy became inseparable from philanthropic practice. By the turn of the millennium, Jewish philanthropic institutions reflected the state's growing investment in capitalism against democratic interests. But well before that, Jewish philanthropy had already entered into a tight relationship with the governing forces of American life, reinforcing and even transforming the nation's laws and policies.The American Jewish Philanthropic Complex uncovers how capitalism and private interests came to command authority over the public good, in Jewish life and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCharity organizationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aJewszUnited StatesxCharitiesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aAdam Teller.  aAnand Giridharadas.  aChosen Capital: The Jewish Encounter with American Capitalism.  aCommunity and Polity: The Organizational Dynamics of American Jewry.  aDaniel Elazar.  aDov Waxman.  aIsrael.  aJ. J. Goldberg.  aJewish Power: Inside the Jewish Establishment.  aJewish Republicans.  aJewish identity.  aJewish politics.  aJewish.  aJews.  aJonathan Woocher.  aJust Giving: Why Philanthropy is Failing Democracy and How It Can Do Better.  aMax Fisher.  aMichael Steinhardt.  